SUPER RARE Olympic target air rifle  
These vintage rifles are very highly sought after by shooters and collectors.  There are some light handling marks. The finish is completely original and a “collector’s preference”.  In the opening of his excellent novel Point of Impact, Stephen Hunter quotes Colonel Townsend Whelen as saying, "Only accurate rifles are interesting." If that is so, then the 300S is one of the most interesting air rifles ever conceived.  The functioning/firing of this rifle is perfect. I bought it from an experienced air rifle shooter/collector and he had a long conversation with me about "dry firing" a Precision Air Rifle, basically: DON'T DO IT. He never did and I haven't either.  Bipod not included.
_______________________________________________________________________
$300 obo
Feinwerkbau Obendorf/N Model 65 Cal. 4.5/.177
Serial Number: 746XX  Year: 1968  
Made in Germany (Patented) 
SUPER RARE Olympic target air pistol  
These vintage pistols are very highly sought after by shooters and collectors.  
The Model 65 is a truly classic target air pistol.  First introduced in the mid 1960's, it was THE target air pistol for many, many years. I believe that there are still international records held by it. It is a spring piston air pistol which was designed for accuracy, not power.  It is considered recoilless because of a sliding action of the receiver to absorb the recoil.  Cocking and compressing the spring is done by pulling back on a lever on the left side of the gun. There are many variations to the basic design, different barrel lengths, grips, sights, one model with an electronic trigger etc.  The rear sight is completely adjustable as you would expect.  There are some light handling marks. The finish is completely original and a “collector’s preference”.  The functioning/firing of this pistol is perfect. title: For Sale:  Feinwerkbau Obendorf/N Model 65 Cal. 4.5/.177
postcontent:
Feinwerkbau Obendorf/N Model 65 Cal. 4.5/.177
Serial Number: 746XX  Year: 1968  
Made in Germany (Patented) 
SUPER RARE Olympic target air pistol  

These vintage pistols are very highly sought after by shooters and collectors.  
The Model 65 is a truly classic target air pistol.  First introduced in the mid 1960's, it was THE target air pistol for many, many years. I believe that there are still international records held by it. It is a spring piston air pistol which was designed for accuracy, not power.  It is considered recoilless because of a sliding action of the receiver to absorb the recoil.  Cocking and compressing the spring is done by pulling back on a lever on the left side of the gun. There are many variations to the basic design, different barrel lengths, grips, sights, one model with an electronic trigger etc.  The rear sight is completely adjustable as you would expect.  

There are some light handling marks. The finish is completely original and a “collector’s preference”. 

The functioning/firing of this pistol is perfect. I bought it from an experienced air rifle shooter/collector and he had a long conversation with me about "dry firing" a Precision Air Pistol, basically: DON'T DO IT. He never did and I haven't either.  More photos available by request.

title: For Sale:  Ruger M77 mkII .25-06 in B&C stock with Nikon 3-9x40
postcontent:
Used Ruger M77 mkII in .25-06.

It is the stainless steel version with a "varmint" barrel. It's not a heavy target or bull barrel. I think it's the perfect profile - it starts very thick in the chamber area and tapers down towards the muzzle.

The rifle has been bedded into a Bell & Carlson synthetic stock with Brownells Accuglass. The bedding is very tight in the action area and supports the chamber area. Past the chamber area it is free-floated. This was done to make the stock more rigid and keep the fore-end from touching the barrel when pressure is applied from underneath.

This stock is far better than the factory garbage and has swivel studs for mounting slings and bipods. There is an ammo carrier glued to the buttstock.



The scope is a Nikon Buckmasters 3-9x40. This has been an outstanding optic for me in the last few years. Its adjustments are more repeatable than two Leupold VX-II scopes that I've had. Very tolerant of adjusting back and forth for different loads.

It shoots well and I can provide 110yd targets if curious. I'd say it averages 1.5MOA 5-shot groups with almost any ammunition, and will easily print 1-1.25MOA with Remington 100gr. Core-Lokt factory ammo. For whatever reason it seems to shoot well with this stuff.

It's been a superb deer, coyote, and prairie dog gun for me. I have other needs now and am letting it go. 

Total price includes 40 rounds of factory Remington 100gr "core-lokt PSP" (these shoot well out of it), and some cases that are ready for powder and bullets.  

89 remington cases, 60 winchester cases, 19 federal cases.  All trimmed at 2.484" +- .001." They've been tumbled, resized, primer pockets cleaned. 

If the rifle ends up needing to be shipped, I'll have to send the ammunition separately, but will not charge for the ammunition package (I will charge to ship the rifle - likely $30 ground).

Price is firm.  This is a good gun.

postcontent:
My invention is that unlike other products of this nature. Most bed holsters comes with an universal and generic type holster that may or may not fit your pistol, whereas the The Holstarr Rack allows you to use your own personal holster specifically designed for your pistol insuring a secure fit. Being that The Holstarr Rack is a one piece design there are not any movable or attached parts that could wear out or fall off. Ambidextrous in design, The Holstarr Rack can be placed on the left or right side of the bed and the head or foot board of the bed and upside down or right side up to allow for many applications.
